\begin_layout Title
The Slide Rule
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Bernard Czenkusz
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
First the nitty gritty
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To understand the action of a slide rule we have to start from Logarithms.
 I'm using the term Logarithm and log interchangeably.
 Logarithm may be the correct term,
 but everyone I know always calls them logs.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the two equations:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y=\log_{b}x
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=b^{y}
\]

\end_inset


\emph on
These say the same thing
\emph default
,
 one gives 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 (and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

).
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

The other gets 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 (and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

)
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

In this case 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is called the base of the log,
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

and putting 
\begin_inset Formula $x=b^{y}$
\end_inset

 into that first equation:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y=\log_{b}b^{y}
\]

\end_inset

So an example:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
8=2^{3}
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
3=\log_{2}8
\]

\end_inset

To illustrate this,
 here's a graph of 
\begin_inset Formula $\log_{2}x$
\end_inset

 against 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename loggraph.svg
	scale 50

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A point to notice is that no negative 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 values are plotted.
 Logarithms are not defined for negative 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

,
 but the logs themselves do take negative values as 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 becomes less than 1.0
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0.5=2^{-1}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
-1=\log_{2}0.5
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The heart of the matter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here's the magic,
 take two numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $c=b^{p}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d=b^{q}$
\end_inset

,
 so therefore:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p=\log_{b}c
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q=\log_{b}d
\]

\end_inset

We know
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
cd=b^{p}b^{q}=b^{p+q}
\]

\end_inset

To illustrate:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
8\times4=2^{3}\times2^{2}=2\times2\times2\times2\times2=2^{5}=32
\]

\end_inset

Taking the log of both sides,
 and noting that 
